Ploting Pie Chart¶

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
data=pd.read_csv("C:\\Users\\ASUS\\Downloads\\WEEK3 new\\WEEK3\\Food & Beverages\\cafe refresh1.csv")

count_positive = 0
count_negative = 0
count_neutral = 0

for sentiment in data['sentiment']:
    if sentiment == 'Positive':
        count_positive += 1
    else:
        count_negative += 1
total=len(data)
positive_response= (count_positive / total) * 100
negative_response = (count_negative / total) * 100
myexplode = [0.2, 0]
y=[positive_response,negative_response]
plt.pie(y,labels=[str(round(positive_response,2))+"%",str(round(negative_response,2))+"%"],explode = myexplode, shadow = True,colors=["g","r"])
plt.title("Check IN tweet % distribution")
plt.legend(["positive","negative"])
plt.show()

LDA for positive tweets¶

In [4]:
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import CountVectorizer
from sklearn.decomposition import LatentDirichletAllocation

from sklearn.feature_extraction import text

# Read the positive reviews data
positive_reviews = pd.read_csv("C:\\Users\\ASUS\\Downloads\\WEEK3 new\\WEEK3\\Food & Beverages\\cafe refresh1 - Copy.csv")

# Combine reviews into a list
reviews = positive_reviews['tweet'].tolist()

# Create a custom stop words list if needed
custom_stop_words = ["read", "good", "disney", "yorker", "day", "didn", "stay", "great", "check", "booked", "like", "die", "told", "friendly", "clean", "sehr", "das", "zimmer", "und", "nice", "did", "was", "really", "safe", "walk", "close", "got"]

# Extend the default English stop words list with custom stop words
stop_words = list(text.ENGLISH_STOP_WORDS) + custom_stop_words

# Vectorize the text data
vectorizer = CountVectorizer(max_df=0.95, min_df=2, stop_words=stop_words)
X = vectorizer.fit_transform(reviews)

# Apply LDA for topic modeling
num_topics = 5
lda = LatentDirichletAllocation(n_components=num_topics, random_state=42)
lda.fit(X)

# Extract top words for each topic
feature_names = vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()
topics = []
for topic_idx, topic in enumerate(lda.components_):
    top_words_idx = topic.argsort()[-10:]
    top_words = [feature_names[i] for i in top_words_idx]
    topics.append(top_words)

# Print the top words for each topic (possible reasons for positive reviews)
for i, topic in enumerate(topics):
    print(f"Topic {i + 1}: {', '.join(topic)}")

Topic 1: hot, restaurants, cafes, beautiful, coffee, need, sparrows, cafe, inside, bangalore
Topic 2: outside, life, request, definitely, feel, time, place, want, cafe, bangalore
Topic 3: breakfast, area, cup, flight, cafe, best, cafes, tea, way, bangalore
Topic 4: beautiful, coffee, tea, local, shopping, cup, better, book, cafe, bangalore
Topic 5: better, bengaluru, windmills, hot, quick, lounge, coffee, noir, bangalore, cafe

Observation on positive tweet¶

  • ### People in Bangalore love cafes. They are looking for cafes that offer hot coffee and tea, a beautiful environment, and local food.
  • ### People want cafes where they can relax and feel comfortable, either inside or outside.
  • ### People are looking for cafes that are conveniently located, especially near airports and shopping areas.

Recommendation:¶

  • ### Create cafes that offer a variety of hot and cold coffee and tea drinks, as well as local food options.

  • ### Design cafes with a beautiful and inviting atmosphere, both inside and outside.

  • ### Locate cafes in convenient locations, such as near airports and shopping areas.

Word Cloud for positive tweets¶

In [5]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from wordcloud import WordCloud

# Create a word cloud object
wc = WordCloud(background_color="white", max_font_size=50)

# Check the type of the topics variable
if isinstance(topics, list):
    # Convert the topics variable to a list of strings
    topics = [" ".join(topic) for topic in topics]

# Generate the word cloud
wc.generate(" ".join(topics))

# Plot the word cloud
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
plt.imshow(wc)
plt.axis("off")
plt.title("Top Words in Positive Reviews")
plt.show()

LDA for Negative tweets¶

In [7]:
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import CountVectorizer
from sklearn.decomposition import LatentDirichletAllocation
from sklearn.feature_extraction import text

# Read the negative reviews data
negative_reviews = pd.read_csv("C:\\Users\\ASUS\\Downloads\\WEEK3 new\\WEEK3\\Food & Beverages\\cafe refresh1 - Copy (2).csv")

# Combine reviews into a list
reviews = negative_reviews['tweet'].tolist()

# Create a custom stop words list if needed
custom_stop_words = ["read", "good", "disney", "yorker", "day", "didn", "stay", "great", "check", "booked", "like", "die", "told", "friendly", "clean", "sehr", "das", "zimmer", "und", "nice", "did", "was", "really", "safe", "walk", "close", "got"]

# Convert the custom stop words to a list
custom_stop_words = list(custom_stop_words)

# Extend the default English stop words list with custom stop words
stop_words = list(text.ENGLISH_STOP_WORDS) + custom_stop_words

# Vectorize the text data
vectorizer = CountVectorizer(max_df=0.95, min_df=2, stop_words=stop_words)
X = vectorizer.fit_transform(reviews)

# Apply LDA for topic modeling
num_topics = 5
lda = LatentDirichletAllocation(n_components=num_topics, random_state=42)
lda.fit(X)

# Extract top words for each topic
feature_names = vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()
topics = []
for topic_idx, topic in enumerate(lda.components_):
    top_words_idx = topic.argsort()[-10:]
    top_words = [feature_names[i] for i in top_words_idx]
    topics.append(top_words)

# Print the top words for each topic (possible reasons for negative reviews)
for i, topic in enumerate(topics):
    print(f"Topic {i + 1}: {', '.join(topic)}")

Topic 1: cup, hot, hate, cafe, people, coffee, airport, bangalore
Topic 2: hate, people, cafe, bangalore, airport, cup, hot, coffee
Topic 3: cup, hot, hate, cafe, people, coffee, airport, bangalore
Topic 4: cup, hot, hate, cafe, people, coffee, airport, bangalore
Topic 5: cup, hot, coffee, people, hate, airport, cafe, bangalore

Observation on negative tweet¶

  • ### People hate hot coffee in Bangalore airport cafes.
  • ### People find the coffee to be overpriced.
  • ### People find the coffee to be of poor quality.
  • ### People find the service to be slow and inefficient.
  • ### People find the cafes to be unclean and unhygeienic.

Recommendation:¶

  • ### Improve the quality of the coffee.
  • ### Reduce the price of the coffee.
  • ### Improve the speed and efficiency of the service.
  • ### Clean and sanitize the cafes more regularly.
